@Prev "Invoking uucp"
@Toc "Invoking uucp"

uucp Description
----------------

     uucp [options] @{b}source-file@{ub} @{b}destination-file@{ub}
uucp [options] @{b}source-file@{ub}... @{b}destination-directory@{ub}

   The @{b}uucp@{ub} command copies files between systems.  Each @{b}file@{ub} argument
is either a file name on the local machine or is of the form
@{b}system!file@{ub}.  The latter is interpreted as being on a remote
system.

   When @{b}uucp@{ub} is used with two non-option arguments, the contents of the
first file are copied to the second.  With more than two non-option
arguments, each source file is copied into the destination directory.

   A file may be transferred to or from @{b}system2@{ub} via @{b}system1@{ub} by using
@{b}system1!system2!file@{ub}.

   Any file name that does not begin with @{b}/@{ub} or @{b}~@{ub} will be prepended with
the current directory (unless the @{b}-W@{ub} or @{b}--noexpand@{ub} options are used).
For example, if you are in the directory @{b}/home/ian@{ub}, then @{b}uucp foo
remote!bar@{ub} is equivalent to @{b}uucp /home/ian/foo
remote!/home/ian/bar@{ub}.  Note that the resulting file name may not
be valid on a remote system.

   A file name beginning with a simple @{b}~@{ub} starts at the UUCP public
directory; a file name beginning with @{b}~name@{ub} starts at the home
directory of the named user.  The @{b}~@{ub} is interpreted on the appropriate
system.  Note that some shells will interpret an initial @{b}~@{ub} before @{b}uucp@{ub}
sees it; to avoid this the @{b}~@{ub} must be quoted.

   The shell metacharacters @{b}?@{ub} @{b}*@{ub} @{b}[@{ub} and @{b}]@{ub} are interpreted on the
appropriate system, assuming they are quoted to prevent the shell from
interpreting them first.

   The file copy does not take place immediately, but is queued up for
the @{b}uucico@{ub} daemon; the daemon is started immediately unless the @{b}-r@{ub} or
@{b}--nouucico@{ub} option is given.  The next time the remote system
is called, the file(s) will be copied.  See @{"Invoking uucico" Link "Invoking uucico"}.

   The file mode is not preserved, except for the execute bit.  The
resulting file is owned by the uucp user.


@EndNode

@Node "uucp Options" "uucp.info/uucp Options"
@Prev "uucp Description"
@Toc "Invoking uucp"

uucp Options
------------

   The following options may be given to @{b}uucp@{ub}.

@{b}-c@{ub}
@{b}--nocopy@{ub}
     Do not copy local source files to the spool directory.  If they are
     removed before being processed by the @{b}uucico@{ub} daemon, the copy will
     fail.  The files must be readable by the @{b}uucico@{ub} daemon, and by the
     invoking user.

@{b}-C@{ub}
@{b}--copy@{ub}
     Copy local source files to the spool directory.  This is the
     default.

@{b}-d@{ub}
@{b}--directories@{ub}
     Create all necessary directories when doing the copy.  This is the
     default.

@{b}-f@{ub}
@{b}--nodirectories@{ub}
     If any necessary directories do not exist for the destination file
     name, abort the copy.

@{b}-R@{ub}
@{b}--recursive@{ub}
     If any of the source file names are directories, copy their
     contents recursively to the destination (which must itself be a
     directory).

@{b}-g grade@{ub}
@{b}--grade grade@{ub}
     Set the grade of the file transfer command.  Jobs of a higher
     grade are executed first.  Grades run @{b}0@{ub} to @{b}9@{ub}, @{b}A@{ub} to @{b}Z@{ub}, @{b}a@{ub} to @{b}z@{ub}, from
     high to low.  See @{"When to Call" Link "When to Call"}.

@{b}-m@{ub}
@{b}--mail@{ub}
     Report completion or failure of the file transfer by sending mail.

@{b}-n user@{ub}
@{b}--notify user@{ub}
     Report completion or failure of the file transfer by sending mail
     to the named user on the destination system.

@{b}-r@{ub}
@{b}--nouucico@{ub}
     Do not start the @{b}uucico@{ub} daemon immediately; merely queue up the
     file transfer for later execution.

@{b}-j@{ub}
@{b}--jobid@{ub}
     Print the jobid on standard output.  The job may be later
     cancelled by passing this jobid to the @{b}-kill@{ub} switch of @{b}uustat@{ub}.
     See @{"Invoking uustat" Link "Invoking uustat"}.

     It is possible for some complex operations to produce more than one
     jobid, in which case each will be printed on a separate line.  For
     example
          uucp sys1!~user1/file1 sys2!~user2/file2 ~user3
     will generate two separate jobs, one for the system @{b}sys1@{ub} and one
     for the system @{b}sys2@{ub}.

@{b}-W@{ub}
@{b}--noexpand@{ub}
     Do not prepend remote relative file names with the current
     directory.

@{b}-t@{ub}
@{b}--uuto@{ub}
     This option is used by the @{b}uuto@{ub} shell script; see @{"Invoking uuto" Link "Invoking uuto"}.
     It causes @{b}uucp@{ub} to interpret the final argument as @{b}system!user@{ub}.
     The file(s) are sent to @{b}~/receive/@{I}USER@{ui}/@{I}LOCAL@{ui}@{ub} on the remote system,
     where @{I}USER@{ui} is from the final argument and @{I}LOCAL@{ui} is the local UUCP
     system name.  Also, @{b}uucp@{ub} will act as though @{b}--notify user@{ub} were
     specified.

@{b}-x type@{ub}
@{b}--debug type@{ub}
@{b}-I file@{ub}
@{b}--config file@{ub}
@{b}-v@{ub}
@{b}--version@{ub}
@{b}--help@{ub}
     See @{"Standard Options" Link "Standard Options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking uux" "uucp.info/Invoking uux"
@Next "Invoking uustat"
@Prev "Invoking uucp"
@Toc "Invoking the UUCP Programs"

Invoking uux
============


 @{" uux Description           " Link "uux Description"}  Description of uux
 @{" uux Options               " Link "uux Options"}  Options Supported by uux
 @{" uux Examples              " Link "uux Examples"}  Examples of uux Usage


@EndNode

@Node "uux Description" "uucp.info/uux Description"
@Next "uux Options"
@Prev "Invoking uux"
@Toc "Invoking uux"

uux Description
---------------

     uux [options] command

   The @{b}uux@{ub} command is used to execute a command on a remote system, or
to execute a command on the local system using files from remote
systems.  The command is not executed immediately; the request is queued
until the @{b}uucico@{ub} daemon calls the system and transfers the necessary
files.  The daemon is started automatically unless one of the @{b}-r@{ub} or
@{b}--nouucico@{ub} options is given.

   The actual command execution is done by the @{b}uuxqt@{ub} daemon on the
appropriate system.

   File arguments can be gathered from remote systems to the execution
system, as can standard input.  Standard output may be directed to a
file on a remote system.

   The command name may be preceded by a system name followed by an
exclamation point if it is to be executed on a remote system.  An empty
system name is taken as the local system.

   Each argument that contains an exclamation point is treated as
naming a file.  The system which the file is on is before the
exclamation point, and the file name on that system follows it.  An
empty system name is taken as the local system; this form must be used
to transfer a file to a command being executed on a remote system.  If
the file name is not absolute, the current working directory will be
prepended to it; the result may not be meaningful on the remote system.
A file name may begin with @{b}~/@{ub}, in which case it is relative to the
UUCP public directory on the appropriate system.  A file name may begin
with @{b}~name/@{ub}, in which case it is relative to the home directory of the
named user on the appropriate system.

   Standard input and output may be redirected as usual; the file names
used may contain exclamation points to indicate that they are on remote
systems.  Note that the redirection characters must be quoted so that
they are passed to @{b}uux@{ub} rather than interpreted by the shell.  Append
redirection (@{b}>>@{ub}) does not work.

   All specified files are gathered together into a single directory
before execution of the command begins.  This means that each file must
have a distinct name.  For example,
     uux 'sys1!diff sys2!~user1/foo sys3!~user2/foo >!foo.diff'
   will fail because both files will be copied to @{b}sys1@{ub} and stored under
the name @{b}foo@{ub}.

   Arguments may be quoted by parentheses to avoid interpretation of
exclamation points.  This is useful when executing the @{b}uucp@{ub} command on
a remote system.

   Most systems restrict the commands which may be executed using @{b}uux@{ub}.
Many permit only the execution of @{b}rmail@{ub} and @{b}rnews@{ub}.

   A request to execute an empty command (e.g., @{b}uux sys!@{ub}) will create a
poll file for the specified system; see @{"Calling Other Systems" Link "Calling Other Systems"} for an
example of why this might be useful.


@EndNode

@Node "uux Options" "uucp.info/uux Options"
@Next "uux Examples"
@Prev "uux Description"
@Toc "Invoking uux"

uux Options
-----------

   The following options may be given to @{b}uux@{ub}.

@{b}-@{ub}
@{b}-p@{ub}
@{b}--stdin@{ub}
     Read standard input up to end of file, and use it as the standard
     input for the command to be executed.

@{b}-c@{ub}
@{b}--nocopy@{ub}
     Do not copy local files to the spool directory.  This is the
     default.  If they are removed before being processed by the @{b}uucico@{ub}
     daemon, the copy will fail.  The files must be readable by the @{b}uucico@{ub}
     daemon, as well as the by the invoker of @{b}uux@{ub}.

@{b}-C@{ub}
@{b}--copy@{ub}
     Copy local files to the spool directory.

@{b}-l@{ub}
@{b}--link@{ub}
     Link local files into the spool directory.  If a file can not be
     linked because it is on a different device, it will be copied
     unless one of the @{b}-c@{ub} or @{b}--nocopy@{ub} options also appears (in other
     words, use of @{b}--link@{ub} switches the default from @{b}--nocopy@{ub} to
     @{b}--copy@{ub}).  If the files are changed before being processed
     by the @{b}uucico@{ub} daemon, the changed versions will be used.  The
     files must be readable by the @{b}uucico@{ub} daemon, as well as by the
     invoker of @{b}uux@{ub}.

@{b}-g grade@{ub}
@{b}--grade grade@{ub}
     Set the grade of the file transfer command.  Jobs of a higher
     grade are executed first.  Grades run @{b}0@{ub} to @{b}9@{ub}, @{b}A@{ub} to @{b}Z@{ub}, @{b}a@{ub} to @{b}z@{ub}, from
     high to low.  See @{"When to Call" Link "When to Call"}.

@{b}-n@{ub}
@{b}--notification=no@{ub}
     Do not send mail about the status of the job, even if it fails.

@{b}-z@{ub}
@{b}--notification=error@{ub}
     Send mail about the status of the job if an error occurs.  For many
     @{b}uuxqt@{ub} daemons, including the Taylor UUCP @{b}uuxqt@{ub}, this is the
     default action; for those, @{b}--notification=error@{ub} will have no
     effect.  However, some @{b}uuxqt@{ub} daemons will send mail if the job
     succeeds, unless the @{b}--notification=error@{ub} option is used.  Some
     other @{b}uuxqt@{ub} daemons will not send mail even if the job fails,
     unless the @{b}--notification=error@{ub} option is used.

@{b}-a address@{ub}
@{b}--requestor address@{ub}
     Report job status, as controlled by the @{b}--notification@{ub} option, to
     the specified mail address.

@{b}-r@{ub}
@{b}--nouucico@{ub}
     Do not start the @{b}uucico@{ub} daemon immediately; merely queue up the
     execution request for later processing.

@{b}-j@{ub}
@{b}--jobid@{ub}
     Print the jobid on standard output.  A jobid will be generated for
     each file copy operation required to execute the command.  These
     file copies may be later cancelled by passing the jobid to the
     @{b}-kill@{ub} switch of @{b}uustat@{ub}.  See @{"Invoking uustat" Link "Invoking uustat"}.  Cancelling
     any file copies will make it impossible to complete execution of
     the job.

@{b}-x type@{ub}
@{b}--debug type@{ub}
@{b}-v@{ub}
@{b}--version@{ub}
@{b}--help@{ub}
     See @{"Standard Options" Link "Standard Options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "uux Examples" "uucp.info/uux Examples"
@Prev "uux Options"
@Toc "Invoking uux"

uux Examples
------------

   Here are some examples of using @{b}uux@{ub}.

     uux -z - sys1!rmail user1
   This will execute the command @{b}rmail user1@{ub} on the system @{b}sys1@{ub}, giving
it as standard input whatever is given to @{b}uux@{ub} as standard input.  If a
failure occurs, mail will be sent to the user who ran the command.

     uux 'diff -c sys1!~user1/file1 sys2!~user2/file2 >!file.diff'
   This will fetch the two named files from system @{b}sys1@{ub} and system @{b}sys2@{ub}
and execute @{b}diff@{ub}, putting the result in @{b}file.diff@{ub} in the current
directory on the local system.  The current directory must be writable
by the @{b}uuxqt@{ub} daemon for this to work.

     uux 'sys1!uucp ~user1/file1 (sys2!~user2/file2)'
   Execute @{b}uucp@{ub} on the system @{b}sys1@{ub} copying @{b}file1@{ub} (on system @{b}sys1@{ub}) to
@{b}sys2@{ub}.  This illustrates the use of parentheses for quoting.


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking uustat" "uucp.info/Invoking uustat"
@Next "Invoking uuname"
@Prev "Invoking uux"
@Toc "Invoking the UUCP Programs"

Invoking uustat
===============


 @{" uustat Description        " Link "uustat Description"}  Description of uustat
 @{" uustat Options            " Link "uustat Options"}  Options Supported by uustat
 @{" uustat Examples           " Link "uustat Examples"}  Examples of uustat Usage


@EndNode

@Node "uustat Description" "uucp.info/uustat Description"
@Next "uustat Options"
@Prev "Invoking uustat"
@Toc "Invoking uustat"

uustat Description
------------------

     uustat -a
uustat --all
uustat [-eKRiMNQ] [-sS system] [-uU user] [-cC command] [-oy hours]
       [-B lines] [--executions] [--kill-all] [--rejuvenate-all]
       [--prompt] [--mail] [--notify] [--no-list] [--system system]
       [--not-system system] [--user user] [--not-user user]
       [--command command] [--not-command command] [--older-than hours]
       [--younger-than hours] [--mail-lines lines]
uustat [-kr jobid] [--kill jobid] [--rejuvenate jobid]
uustat -q [-sS system] [-oy hours] [--system system]
       [--not-system system ] [--older-than hours] [--younger-than hours]
uustat --list [-sS system] [-oy hours] [--system system ]
       [--not-system system] [--older-than hours] [--younger-than hours]
uustat -m
uustat --status
uustat -p
uustat --ps

   The @{b}uustat@{ub} command can display various types of status information
about the UUCP system.  It can also be used to cancel or rejuvenate
requests made by @{b}uucp@{ub} or @{b}uux@{ub}.

   With no options, @{b}uustat@{ub} displays all jobs queued up for the invoking
user, as if given the @{b}--user@{ub} option with the appropriate argument.

   If any of the @{b}-a@{ub}, @{b}--all@{ub}, @{b}-e@{ub}, @{b}--executions@{ub}, @{b}-s@{ub}, @{b}--system@{ub}, @{b}-S@{ub},
@{b}--not-system@{ub}, @{b}-u@{ub}, @{b}--user@{ub}, @{b}-U@{ub}, @{b}--not-user@{ub}, @{b}-c@{ub}, @{b}--command@{ub}, @{b}-C@{ub},
@{b}--not-command@{ub}, @{b}-o@{ub}, @{b}--older-than@{ub}, @{b}-y@{ub}, or @{b}--younger-than@{ub} options
are given, then all jobs which match the combined specifications are
displayed.

   The @{b}-K@{ub} or @{b}--kill-all@{ub} option may be used to kill off a selected group
of jobs, such as all jobs more than 7 days old.


@EndNode

@Node "uustat Options" "uucp.info/uustat Options"
@Next "uustat Examples"
@Prev "uustat Description"
@Toc "Invoking uustat"

uustat Options
--------------

   The following options may be given to @{b}uustat@{ub}.

@{b}-a@{ub}
@{b}--all@{ub}
     List all queued file transfer requests.

@{b}-e@{ub}
@{b}--executions@{ub}
     List queued execution requests rather than queued file transfer
     requests.  Queued execution requests are processed by @{b}uuxqt@{ub} rather
     than @{b}uucico@{ub}.  Queued execution requests may be waiting for some
     file to be transferred from a remote system.  They are created by
     an invocation of @{b}uux@{ub}.

@{b}-s system@{ub}
@{b}--system system@{ub}
     List all jobs queued up for the named system.  These options may be
     specified multiple times, in which case all jobs for all the named
     systems will be listed.  If used with @{b}--list@{ub}, only the systems
     named will be listed.

@{b}-S system@{ub}
@{b}--not-system system@{ub}
     List all jobs queued for systems other than the one named.  These
     options may be specified multiple times, in which case no jobs
     from any of the specified systems will be listed.  If used with
     @{b}--list@{ub}, only the systems not named will be listed.  These
     options may not be used with @{b}-s@{ub} or @{b}--system@{ub}.

@{b}-u user@{ub}
@{b}--user user@{ub}
     List all jobs queued up for the named user.  These options may be
     specified multiple times, in which case all jobs for all the named
     users will be listed.

@{b}-U user@{ub}
@{b}--not-user user@{ub}
     List all jobs queued up for users other than the one named.  These
     options may be specified multiple times, in which case no jobs
     from any of the specified users will be listed.  These options may
     not be used with @{b}-u@{ub} or @{b}--user@{ub}.

@{b}-c command@{ub}
@{b}--command command@{ub}
     List all jobs requesting the execution of the named command.  If
     @{b}command@{ub} is @{b}ALL@{ub} this will list all jobs requesting the
     execution of some command (as opposed to simply requesting a file
     transfer).  These options may be specified multiple times, in
     which case all jobs requesting any of the commands will be listed.

@{b}-C command@{ub}
@{b}--not-command command@{ub}
     List all jobs requesting execution of some command other than the
     named command, or, if @{b}command@{ub} is @{b}ALL@{ub}, list all jobs that simply
     request a file transfer (as opposed to requesting the execution of
     some command).  These options may be specified multiple times, in
     which case no job requesting one of the specified commands will be
     listed.  These options may not be used with @{b}-c@{ub} or @{b}--command@{ub}.

@{b}-o hours@{ub}
@{b}--older-than hours@{ub}
     List all queued jobs older than the given number of hours.  If
     used with @{b}--list@{ub}, only systems whose oldest job is older than the
     given number of hours will be listed.

@{b}-y hours@{ub}
@{b}--younger-than hours@{ub}
     List all queued jobs younger than the given number of hours.  If
     used with @{b}--list@{ub}, only systems whose oldest job is younger than the
     given number of hours will be listed.

@{b}-k jobid@{ub}
@{b}--kill jobid@{ub}
     Kill the named job.  The job id is shown by the default output
     format, as well as by the @{b}-j@{ub} or @{b}--jobid@{ub} options to @{b}uucp@{ub} or @{b}uux@{ub}.  A
     job may only be killed by the user who created the job, or by the
     UUCP administrator, or the superuser.  The @{b}-k@{ub} or @{b}--kill@{ub} options
     may be used multiple times on the command line to kill several
     jobs.

@{b}-r jobid@{ub}
@{b}--rejuvenate jobid@{ub}
     Rejuvenate the named job.  This will mark it as having been
     invoked at the current time, affecting the output of the @{b}-o@{ub},
     @{b}--older-than@{ub}, @{b}-y@{ub}, or @{b}--younger-than@{ub} options, possibly
     preserving it from any automated cleanup daemon.  The job id is
     shown by the default output format, as well as by the @{b}-j@{ub} or
     @{b}--jobid@{ub} options to @{b}uucp@{ub} or @{b}uux@{ub}.  A job may only be
     rejuvenated by the user who created the job, or by the UUCP
     administrator, or the superuser.  The @{b}-r@{ub} or @{b}--rejuvenate@{ub} options
     may be used multiple times on the command line to rejuvenate
     several jobs.

@{b}-q@{ub}
@{b}--list@{ub}
     Display the status of commands, executions and conversations for
     all remote systems for which commands or executions are queued.
     The @{b}-s@{ub}, @{b}--system@{ub}, @{b}-S@{ub}, @{b}--not-system@{ub}, @{b}-o@{ub}, @{b}--older-than@{ub}, @{b}-y@{ub}, and
     @{b}--younger-than@{ub} options may be used to restrict the
     systems which are listed.  Systems for which no commands or
     executions are queued will never be listed.

@{b}-m@{ub}
@{b}--status@{ub}
     Display the status of conversations for all remote systems.

@{b}-p@{ub}
@{b}--ps@{ub}
     Display the status of all processes holding UUCP locks on systems
     or ports.

@{b}-i@{ub}
@{b}--prompt@{ub}
     For each listed job, prompt whether to kill the job or not.  If the
     first character of the input line is @{b}y@{ub} or @{b}Y@{ub}, the job will be
     killed.

@{b}-K@{ub}
@{b}--kill-all@{ub}
     Automatically kill each listed job.  This can be useful for
     automatic cleanup scripts, in conjunction with the @{b}--mail@{ub} and
     @{b}--notify@{ub} options.

@{b}-R@{ub}
@{b}--rejuvenate-all@{ub}
     Automatically rejuvenate each listed job.  This may not be used
     with @{b}--kill-all@{ub}.

@{b}-M@{ub}
@{b}--mail@{ub}
     For each listed job, send mail to the UUCP administrator.  If the
     job is killed (due to @{b}--kill-all@{ub}, or @{b}--prompt@{ub} with an affirmative
     response) the mail will indicate that.  A comment specified by the
     @{b}--comment@{ub} option may be included.  If the job is an
     execution, the initial portion of its standard input will be
     included in the mail message; the number of lines to include may
     be set with the @{b}--mail-lines@{ub} option (the default is 100).  If the
     standard input contains null characters, it is assumed to be a
     binary file and is not included.

@{b}-N@{ub}
@{b}--notify@{ub}
     For each listed job, send mail to the user who requested the job.
     The mail is identical to that sent by the @{b}-M@{ub} or @{b}--mail@{ub} options.

@{b}-W comment@{ub}
@{b}--comment comment@{ub}
     Specify a comment to be included in mail sent with the @{b}-M@{ub}, @{b}--mail@{ub},
     @{b}-N@{ub}, or @{b}--notify@{ub} options.

@{b}-B lines@{ub}
@{b}--mail-lines lines@{ub}
     When the @{b}-M@{ub}, @{b}--mail@{ub}, @{b}-N@{ub}, or @{b}--notify@{ub} options are used to send mail
     about an execution with standard input, this option controls the
     number of lines of standard input to include in the message.  The
     default is 100.

@{b}-Q@{ub}
@{b}--no-list@{ub}
     Do not actually list the job, but only take any actions indicated
     by the @{b}-i@{ub}, @{b}--prompt@{ub}, @{b}-K@{ub}, @{b}--kill-all@{ub}, @{b}-M@{ub}, @{b}--mail@{ub}, @{b}-N@{ub} or @{b}--notify@{ub}
     options.

@{b}-x type@{ub}
@{b}--debug type@{ub}
@{b}-I file@{ub}
@{b}--config file@{ub}
@{b}-v@{ub}
@{b}--version@{ub}
@{b}--help@{ub}
     See @{"Standard Options" Link "Standard Options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "uustat Examples" "uucp.info/uustat Examples"
@Prev "uustat Options"
@Toc "Invoking uustat"

uustat Examples
---------------

     uustat --all
   Display status of all jobs.  A sample output line is as follows:
     bugsA027h bugs ian 04-01 13:50 Executing rmail ian@airs.com (sending 12 bytes)
   The format is
     jobid system user queue-date command (size)
   The jobid may be passed to the @{b}--kill@{ub} or @{b}--rejuvenate@{ub} options.  The
size indicates how much data is to be transferred to the remote system,
and is absent for a file receive request.  The @{b}--system@{ub}, @{b}--not-system@{ub},
@{b}--user@{ub}, @{b}--not-user@{ub}, @{b}--command@{ub}, @{b}--not-command@{ub}, @{b}--older-than@{ub}, and
@{b}--younger-than@{ub} options may be used to control which jobs are listed.

     uustat --executions
   Display status of queued up execution requests.  A sample output line
is as follows:
     bugs bugs!ian 05-20 12:51 rmail ian
   The format is
     system requestor queue-date command
   The @{b}--system@{ub}, @{b}--not-system@{ub}, @{b}--user@{ub}, @{b}--not-user@{ub}, @{b}--command@{ub},
@{b}--not-command@{ub}, @{b}--older-than@{ub}, and @{b}--younger-than@{ub} options may be
used to control which requests are listed.

     uustat --list
   Display status for all systems with queued up commands.  A sample
output line is as follows:
     bugs            4C (1 hour)   0X (0 secs) 04-01 14:45 Dial failed
   This indicates the system, the number of queued commands, the age of
the oldest queued command, the number of queued local executions, the
age of the oldest queued execution, the date of the last conversation,
and the status of that conversation.

     uustat --status
   Display conversation status for all remote systems.  A sample output
line is as follows:
     bugs           04-01 15:51 Conversation complete
   This indicates the system, the date of the last conversation, and the
status of that conversation.  If the last conversation failed, @{b}uustat@{ub}
will indicate how many attempts have been made to call the system.  If
the retry period is currently preventing calls to that system, @{b}uustat@{ub}
also displays the time when the next call will be permitted.

     uustat --ps
   Display the status of all processes holding UUCP locks.  The output
format is system dependent, as @{b}uustat@{ub} simply invokes @{b}ps@{ub} on each process
holding a lock.

     uustat -c rmail -o 168 -K -Q -M -N -W "Queued for over 1 week"
   This will kill all @{b}rmail@{ub} commands that have been queued up waiting
for delivery for over 1 week (168 hours).  For each such command, mail
will be sent both to the UUCP administrator and to the user who
requested the rmail execution.  The mail message sent will include the
string given by the @{b}-W@{ub} option.  The @{b}-Q@{ub} option prevents any of the jobs
from being listed on the terminal, so any output from the program will
be error messages.


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking uuname" "uucp.info/Invoking uuname"
@Next "Invoking uulog"
@Prev "Invoking uustat"
@Toc "Invoking the UUCP Programs"

Invoking uuname
===============

     uuname [-a] [--aliases]
uuname -l
uuname --local

   By default, the @{b}uuname@{ub} program simply lists the names of all the
remote systems mentioned in the UUCP configuration files.

   The @{b}uuname@{ub} program may also be used to print the UUCP name of the
local system.

   The @{b}uuname@{ub} program is mainly for use by shell scripts.

   The following options may be given to @{b}uuname@{ub}.

@{b}-a@{ub}
@{b}--aliases@{ub}
     List all aliases for remote systems, as well as their canonical
     names.  Aliases may be specified in the @{b}sys@{ub} file (see
     @{"Naming the System" Link "Naming the System"}).

@{b}-l@{ub}
@{b}--local@{ub}
     Print the UUCP name of the local system, rather than listing the
     names of all the remote systems.

@{b}-x type@{ub}
@{b}--debug type@{ub}
@{b}-I file@{ub}
@{b}--config file@{ub}
@{b}-v@{ub}
@{b}--version@{ub}
@{b}--help@{ub}
     See @{"Standard Options" Link "Standard Options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking uulog" "uucp.info/Invoking uulog"
@Next "Invoking uuto"
@Prev "Invoking uuname"
@Toc "Invoking the UUCP Programs"

Invoking uulog
==============

     uulog [-#] [-n lines] [-sf system] [-u user] [-DSF] [--lines lines]
      [--system system] [--user user] [--debuglog] [--statslog]
      [--follow] [--follow=system]

   The @{b}uulog@{ub} program may be used to display the UUCP log file.
Different options may be used to select which parts of the file to
display.

@{b}-#@{ub}
@{b}-n lines@{ub}
@{b}--lines lines@{ub}
     Here @{b}#@{ub} is a number; e.g., @{b}-10@{ub}.  The specified number of lines is
     displayed from the end of the log file.  The default is to display
     the entire log file, unless the @{b}-f@{ub}, @{b}-F@{ub}, or @{b}--follow@{ub} options are
     used, in which case the default is to display 10 lines.

@{b}-s system@{ub}
@{b}--system system@{ub}
     Display only log entries pertaining to the specified system.

@{b}-u user@{ub}
@{b}--user user@{ub}
     Display only log entries pertaining to the specified user.

@{b}-D@{ub}
@{b}--debuglog@{ub}
     Display the debugging log file.

@{b}-S@{ub}
@{b}--statslog@{ub}
     Display the statistics log file.

@{b}-F@{ub}
@{b}--follow@{ub}
     Keep displaying the log file forever, printing new lines as they
     are appended to the log file.

@{b}-f system@{ub}
@{b}--follow=system@{ub}
     Keep displaying the log file forever, displaying only log entries
     pertaining to the specified system.

@{b}-X type@{ub}
@{b}--debug type@{ub}
@{b}-I file@{ub}
@{b}--config file@{ub}
@{b}-v@{ub}
@{b}--version@{ub}
@{b}--help@{ub}
     See @{"Standard Options" Link "Standard Options"}.  Note that @{b}uulog@{ub} specifies the debugging
     type using @{b}-X@{ub} rather than the usual @{b}-x@{ub}.

   The operation of @{b}uulog@{ub} depends to some degree upon the type of log
files generated by the UUCP programs.  This is a compile time option.
If the UUCP programs have been compiled to use HDB style log files,
@{b}uulog@{ub} changes in the following ways:

   @{b}*@{ub} The new options @{b}-x@{ub} and @{b}--uuxqtlog@{ub} may be used to list the @{b}uuxqt@{ub}
     log file.

   @{b}*@{ub} It is no longer possible to omit all arguments: one of @{b}-s@{ub},
     @{b}--system@{ub}, @{b}-f@{ub}, @{b}--follow=system@{ub}, @{b}-D@{ub}, @{b}--debuglog@{ub}, @{b}-S@{ub},
     @{b}--statslog@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}, or @{b}--uuxqtlog@{ub} must be used.

   @{b}*@{ub} The option @{b}--system ANY@{ub} may be used to list log file entries which
     do not pertain to any particular system.


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking uuto" "uucp.info/Invoking uuto"
@Next "Invoking uupick"
@Prev "Invoking uulog"
@Toc "Invoking the UUCP Programs"

Invoking uuto
=============

     uuto files... system!user

   The @{b}uuto@{ub} program may be used to conveniently send files to a
particular user on a remote system.  It will arrange for mail to be sent
to the remote user when the files arrive on the remote system, and he or
she may easily retrieve the files using the @{b}uupick@{ub} program (see
@{"Invoking uupick" Link "Invoking uupick"}).  Note that @{b}uuto@{ub} does not provide any security--any
user on the remote system can examine the files.

   The last argument specifies the system and user name to which to send
the files.  The other arguments are the files or directories to be sent.

   The @{b}uuto@{ub} program is actually just a trivial shell script which
invokes the @{b}uucp@{ub} program with the appropriate arguments.  Any option
which may be given to @{b}uucp@{ub} may also be given to @{b}uuto@{ub}.  See
@{"Invoking uucp" Link "Invoking uucp"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking uupick" "uucp.info/Invoking uupick"
@Next "Invoking cu"
@Prev "Invoking uuto"
@Toc "Invoking the UUCP Programs"

Invoking uupick
===============

     uupick [-s system] [--system system]

   The @{b}uupick@{ub} program is used to conveniently retrieve files
transferred by the @{b}uuto@{ub} program.

   For each file transferred by @{b}uuto@{ub}, @{b}uupick@{ub} will display the source
system, the file name, and whether the name refers to a regular file or
a directory.  It will then wait for the user to specify an action to
take.  One of the following commands must be entered:

@{b}q@{ub}
     Quit out of @{b}uupick@{ub}.

@{b}RETURN@{ub}
     Skip the file.

@{b}m [directory]@{ub}
     Move the file or directory to the specified directory.  If no
     directory is specified, the file is moved to the current directory.

@{b}a [directory]@{ub}
     Move all files from this system to the specified directory.  If no
     directory is specified, the files are moved to the current
     directory.

@{b}p@{ub}
     List the file on standard output.

@{b}d@{ub}
     Delete the file.

@{b}! [command]@{ub}
     Execute @{b}command@{ub} as a shell escape.

   The @{b}-s@{ub} or @{b}--system@{ub} option may be used to restrict @{b}uupick@{ub} to only
present files transferred from a particular system.  The @{b}uupick@{ub} program
also supports the standard UUCP program options; see @{"Standard Options" Link "Standard Options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking cu" "uucp.info/Invoking cu"
@Next "Invoking uucico"
@Prev "Invoking uupick"
@Toc "Invoking the UUCP Programs"

Invoking cu
===========


 @{" cu Description            " Link "cu Description"}  Description of cu
 @{" cu Commands               " Link "cu Commands"}  Commands Supported by cu
 @{" cu Variables              " Link "cu Variables"}  Variables Supported by cu
 @{" cu Options                " Link "cu Options"}  Options Supported by cu


@EndNode

@Node "cu Description" "uucp.info/cu Description"
@Next "cu Commands"
@Prev "Invoking cu"
@Toc "Invoking cu"

cu Description
--------------

     cu [options] [system | phone | "dir"]

   The @{b}cu@{ub} program is used to call up another system and act as a dial
in terminal.  It can also do simple file transfers with no error
checking.

   The @{b}cu@{ub} program takes a single non-option argument.

   If the argument is the string @{b}dir@{ub} cu will make a direct connection
to the port.  This may only be used by users with write access to the
port, as it permits reprogramming the modem.

   Otherwise, if the argument begins with a digit, it is taken to be a
phone number to call.

   Otherwise, it is taken to be the name of a system to call.

   The @{b}-z@{ub} or @{b}--system@{ub} options may be used to name a system beginning
with a digit, and the @{b}-c@{ub} or @{b}--phone@{ub} options may be used to name a phone
number that does not begin with a digit.

   The @{b}cu@{ub} program locates a port to use in the UUCP configuration
files.  If a simple system name is given, it will select a port
appropriate for that system.  The @{b}-p@{ub}, @{b}--port@{ub}, @{b}-l@{ub}, @{b}--line@{ub}, @{b}-s@{ub}, and
@{b}--speed@{ub} options may be used to control the port selection.

   When a connection is made to the remote system, @{b}cu@{ub} forks into two
processes.  One reads from the port and writes to the terminal, while
the other reads from the terminal and writes to the port.


@EndNode

@Node "cu Commands" "uucp.info/cu Commands"
@Next "cu Variables"
@Prev "cu Description"
@Toc "Invoking cu"

cu Commands
-----------

   The @{b}cu@{ub} program provides several commands that may be used during the
conversation.  The commands all begin with an escape character, which
by default is @{b}~@{ub} (tilde).  The escape character is only recognized at
the beginning of a line.  To send an escape character to the remote
system at the start of a line, it must be entered twice.  All commands
are either a single character or a word beginning with @{b}%@{ub} (percent sign).

   The @{b}cu@{ub} program recognizes the following commands.

@{b}~.@{ub}
     Terminate the conversation.

@{b}~! command@{ub}
     Run command in a shell.  If command is empty, starts up a shell.

@{b}~$ command@{ub}
     Run command, sending the standard output to the remote system.

@{b}~| command@{ub}
     Run command, taking the standard input from the remote system.

@{b}~+ command@{ub}
     Run command, taking the standard input from the remote system and
     sending the standard output to the remote system.

@{b}~#, ~%break@{ub}
     Send a break signal, if possible.

@{b}~c directory, ~%cd directory@{ub}
     Change the local directory.

@{b}~> file@{ub}
     Send a file to the remote system.  This just dumps the file over
     the communication line.  It is assumed that the remote system is
     expecting it.

@{b}~<@{ub}
     Receive a file from the remote system.  This prompts for the local
     file name and for the remote command to execute to begin the file
     transfer.  It continues accepting data until the contents of the @{b}eofread@{ub}
     variable are seen.

@{b}~p from to@{ub}
@{b}~%put from to@{ub}
     Send a file to a remote Unix system.  This runs the appropriate
     commands on the remote system.

@{b}~t from to@{ub}
@{b}~%take from to@{ub}
     Retrieve a file from a remote Unix system.  This runs the
     appropriate commands on the remote system.

@{b}~s variable value@{ub}
     Set a @{b}cu@{ub} variable to the given value.  If value is not given, the
     variable is set to @{b}true@{ub}.

@{b}~! variable@{ub}
     Set a @{b}cu@{ub} variable to @{b}false@{ub}.

@{b}~z@{ub}
     Suspend the cu session.  This is only supported on some systems.
     On systems for which @{b}^Z@{ub} may be used to suspend a job, @{b}~^Z@{ub} will
     also suspend the session.

@{b}~%nostop@{ub}
     Turn off XON/XOFF handling.

@{b}~%stop@{ub}
     Turn on XON/XOFF handling.

@{b}~v@{ub}
     List all the variables and their values.

@{b}~?@{ub}
     List all commands.


@EndNode

@Node "cu Variables" "uucp.info/cu Variables"
@Next "cu Options"
@Prev "cu Commands"
@Toc "Invoking cu"

cu Variables
------------

   The @{b}cu@{ub} program also supports several variables.  They may be listed
with the @{b}~v@{ub} command, and set with the @{b}~s@{ub} or @{b}~!@{ub}  commands.

@{b}escape@{ub}
     The escape character.  The default is @{b}~@{ub} (tilde).

@{b}delay@{ub}
     If this variable is true, @{b}cu@{ub} will delay for a second, after
     recognizing the escape character, before printing the name of the
     local system.  The default is true.

@{b}eol@{ub}
     The list of characters which are considered to finish a line.  The
     escape character is only recognized after one of these is seen.
     The default is @{b}carriage return@{ub}, @{b}^U@{ub}, @{b}^C@{ub}, @{b}^O@{ub}, @{b}^D@{ub}, @{b}^S@{ub}, @{b}^Q@{ub}, @{b}^R@{ub}.

@{b}binary@{ub}
     Whether to transfer binary data when sending a file.  If this is
     false, then newlines in the file being sent are converted to
     carriage returns.  The default is false.

@{b}binary-prefix@{ub}
     A string used before sending a binary character in a file
     transfer, if the @{b}binary@{ub} variable is true.  The default is @{b}^V@{ub}.

@{b}echo-check@{ub}
     Whether to check file transfers by examining what the remote system
     echoes back.  This probably doesn't work very well.  The default is
     false.

@{b}echonl@{ub}
     The character to look for after sending each line in a file.  The
     default is carriage return.

@{b}timeout@{ub}
     The timeout to use, in seconds, when looking for a character,
     either when doing echo checking or when looking for the @{b}echonl@{ub}
     character.  The default is 30.

@{b}kill@{ub}
     The character to use delete a line if the echo check fails.  The
     default is @{b}^U@{ub}.

@{b}resend@{ub}
     The number of times to resend a line if the echo check continues to
     fail.  The default is 10.

@{b}eofwrite@{ub}
     The string to write after sending a file with the @{b}~>@{ub} command.  The
     default is @{b}^D@{ub}.

@{b}eofread@{ub}
     The string to look for when receiving a file with the @{b} ~<@{ub} command.
     The default is @{b}$@{ub}, which is intended to be a typical shell prompt.

@{b}verbose@{ub}
     Whether to print accumulated information during a file transfer.
     The default is true.


@EndNode

@Node "cu Options" "uucp.info/cu Options"
@Prev "cu Variables"
@Toc "Invoking cu"

cu Options
----------

   The following options may be given to @{b}cu@{ub}.

@{b}-e@{ub}
@{b}--parity=even@{ub}
     Use even parity.

@{b}-o@{ub}
@{b}--parity=odd@{ub}
     Use odd parity.

@{b}--parity=none@{ub}
     Use no parity.  No parity is also used if both @{b}-e@{ub} and @{b}-o@{ub} are given.

@{b}-h@{ub}
@{b}--halfduplex@{ub}
     Echo characters locally (half-duplex mode).

@{b}--nostop@{ub}
     Turn off XON/XOFF handling (it is on by default).

@{b}-E char@{ub}
@{b}--escape char@{ub}
     Set the escape character.  Initially @{b}~@{ub} (tilde).  To eliminate the
     escape character, use @{b}-E ''@{ub}.

@{b}-z system@{ub}
@{b}--system system@{ub}
     The system to call.

@{b}-c phone-number@{ub}
@{b}--phone phone-number@{ub}
     The phone number to call.

@{b}-p port@{ub}
@{b}-a port@{ub}
@{b}--port port@{ub}
     Name the port to use.

@{b}-l line@{ub}
@{b}--line line@{ub}
     Name the line to use by giving a device name.  This may be used to
     dial out on ports that are not listed in the UUCP configuration
     files.  Write access to the device is required.

@{b}-s speed@{ub}
@{b}-#@{ub}
@{b}--speed speed@{ub}
     The speed (baud rate) to use.  Here, @{b}-#@{ub} means an actual number;
     e.g., @{b}-9600@{ub}.

@{b}-n@{ub}
@{b}--prompt@{ub}
     Prompt for the phone number to use.

@{b}-d@{ub}
     Enter debugging mode.  Equivalent to @{b}--debug all@{ub}.

@{b}-x type@{ub}
@{b}--debug type@{ub}
@{b}-I file@{ub}
@{b}--config file@{ub}
@{b}-v@{ub}
@{b}--version@{ub}
@{b}--help@{ub}
     See @{"Standard Options" Link "Standard Options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking uucico" "uucp.info/Invoking uucico"
@Next "Invoking uuxqt"
@Prev "Invoking cu"
@Toc "Invoking the UUCP Programs"

Invoking uucico
===============


 @{" uucico Description        " Link "uucico Description"}  Description of uucico
 @{" uucico Options            " Link "uucico Options"}  Options Supported by uucico


@EndNode

@Node "uucico Description" "uucp.info/uucico Description"
@Next "uucico Options"
@Prev "Invoking uucico"
@Toc "Invoking uucico"

uucico Description
------------------

     uucico [options]

   The @{b}uucico@{ub} daemon processes file transfer requests queued by @{b}uucp@{ub}
and @{b}uux@{ub}.  It is started when @{b}uucp@{ub} or @{b}uux@{ub} is run (unless they are given
the @{b}-r@{ub} or @{b}--nouucico@{ub} options).  It is also typically started
periodically using entries in the @{b}crontab@{ub} table(s).

   When @{b}uucico@{ub} is invoked with @{b}-r1@{ub}, @{b}--master@{ub}, @{b}-s@{ub}, @{b}--system@{ub}, or @{b}-S@{ub}, the
daemon will place a call to a remote system, running in master mode.
Otherwise the daemon will start in slave mode, accepting a call from a
remote system.  Typically a special login name will be set up for UUCP
which automatically invokes @{b}uucico@{ub} when a remote system calls in and
logs in under that name.

   When @{b}uucico@{ub} terminates, it invokes the @{b}uuxqt@{ub} daemon, unless the @{b}-q@{ub}
or @{b}--nouuxqt@{ub} options were given; @{b}uuxqt@{ub} executes any work orders created
by @{b}uux@{ub} on a remote system, and any work orders created locally which
have received remote files for which they were waiting.

   If a call fails, @{b}uucico@{ub} will normally refuse to retry the call until
a certain (configurable) amount of time has passed.  This may be
overriden by the @{b}-f@{ub}, @{b}--force@{ub}, or @{b}-S@{ub} options.

   The @{b}-l@{ub}, @{b}--prompt@{ub}, @{b}-e@{ub}, or @{b}--loop@{ub} options may be used to force @{b}uucico@{ub}
to produce its own prompts of @{b}login: @{ub} and @{b}Password:@{ub}.  When another
@{b}uucico@{ub} daemon calls in, it will see these prompts and log in
as usual.  The login name and password will normally be checked against
a separate list kept specially for @{b}uucico@{ub}, rather than the @{b}/etc/passwd@{ub}
file (see @{"Configuration File Names" Link "Configuration File Names"}).  It is possible, on some systems,
to configure @{b}uucico@{ub} to use @{b}/etc/passwd@{ub}.  The @{b}-l@{ub} or @{b}--prompt@{ub} options
will prompt once and then exit; in this mode the UUCP administrator, or
the superuser, may use the @{b}-u@{ub} or @{b}--login@{ub} option to force a login name,
in which case @{b}uucico@{ub} will not prompt for one.  The @{b}-e@{ub} or @{b}--loop@{ub} options
will prompt again after the first session is over; in this mode @{b}uucico@{ub}
will permanently control a port.

   If @{b}uucico@{ub} receives a @{b}SIGQUIT@{ub}, @{b}SIGTERM@{ub} or @{b}SIGPIPE@{ub} signal, it will
cleanly abort any current conversation with a remote system and exit.
If it receives a @{b}SIGHUP@{ub} signal it will abort any current conversation,
but will continue to place calls to (if invoked with @{b}-r1@{ub} or @{b}--master@{ub})
and accept calls from (if invoked with @{b}-e@{ub} or @{b}--loop@{ub}) other systems.  If
it receives a @{b}SIGINT@{ub} signal it will finish the current conversation,
but will not place or accept any more calls.


@EndNode

@Node "uucico Options" "uucp.info/uucico Options"
@Prev "uucico Description"
@Toc "Invoking uucico"

uucico Options
--------------

   The following options may be given to @{b}uucico@{ub}.

@{b}-r1@{ub}
@{b}--master@{ub}
     Start in master mode: call out to a remote system.  Implied by @{b}-s@{ub},
     @{b}--system@{ub}, or @{b}-S@{ub}.  If no system is specified, sequentially
     call every system for which work is waiting to be done.

@{b}-r0@{ub}
@{b}--slave@{ub}
     Start in slave mode.  This is the default.

@{b}-s system@{ub}
@{b}--system system@{ub}
     Call the specified system.

@{b}-S system@{ub}
     Call the specified system, ignoring any required wait.  This is
     equivalent to @{b}-s system -f@{ub}.

@{b}-f@{ub}
@{b}--force@{ub}
     Ignore any required wait for any systems to be called.

@{b}-l@{ub}
@{b}--prompt@{ub}
     Prompt for login name and password using @{b}login: @{ub} and @{b}Password:@{ub}.
     This allows @{b}uucico@{ub} to be easily run from @{b}inetd@{ub}.  The login name
     and password are checked against the UUCP password file, which
     need not be @{b}/etc/passwd@{ub}.  The @{b}--login@{ub} option may be used to force
     a login name, in which cause @{b}uucico@{ub} will only prompt for a
     password.

@{b}-p port@{ub}
@{b}--port port@{ub}
     Specify a port to call out on or to listen to.

@{b}-e@{ub}
@{b}--loop@{ub}
     Enter an endless loop of login/password prompts and slave mode
     daemon execution.  The program will not stop by itself; you must
     use @{b}kill@{ub} to shut it down.

@{b}-w@{ub}
@{b}--wait@{ub}
     After calling out (to a particular system when @{b}-s@{ub}, @{b}--system@{ub}, or @{b}-S@{ub}
     is specifed, or to all systems which have work when just @{b}-r1@{ub} or
     @{b}--master@{ub} is specifed), begin an endless loop as with
     @{b}--loop@{ub}.

@{b}-q@{ub}
@{b}--nouuxqt@{ub}
     Do not start the @{b}uuxqt@{ub} daemon when finished.

@{b}-c@{ub}
@{b}--quiet@{ub}
     If no calls are permitted at this time, then don't make the call,
     but also do not put an error message in the log file and do not
     update the system status (as reported by @{b}uustat@{ub}).  This can be
     convenient for automated polling scripts, which may want to simply
     attempt to call every system rather than worry about which
     particular systems may be called at the moment.  This option also
     suppresses the log message indicating that there is no work to be
     done.

@{b}-C@{ub}
@{b}--ifwork@{ub}
     Only call the system named by @{b}-s@{ub}, @{b}--system@{ub}, or @{b}-S@{ub} if there is work
     for that system.

@{b}-D@{ub}
@{b}--nodetach@{ub}
     Do not detach from the controlling terminal.  Normally @{b}uucico@{ub}
     detaches from the terminal before each call out to another system
     and before invoking @{b}uuxqt@{ub}.  This option prevents this.

@{b}-u name@{ub}
@{b}--login name@{ub}
     Set the login name to use instead of that of the invoking user.
     This option may only be used by the UUCP administrator or the
     superuser.  If used with @{b}--prompt@{ub}, this will cause @{b}uucico@{ub} to
     prompt only for the password, not the login name.

@{b}-z@{ub}
@{b}--try-next@{ub}
     If a call fails after the remote system is reached, try the next
     alternate rather than simply exiting.

@{b}-i type@{ub}
@{b}--stdin type@{ub}
     Set the type of port to use when using standard input.  The only
     supported port type is TLI, and this is only available on machines
     which support the TLI networking interface.  Specifying @{b}-i TLI@{ub}
     causes @{b}uucico@{ub} to use TLI calls to perform I/O.

@{b}-X type@{ub}
     Same as the standard option @{b}-x type@{ub}.  Provided for historical
     compatibility.

@{b}-x type@{ub}
@{b}--debug type@{ub}
@{b}-I file@{ub}
@{b}--config file@{ub}
@{b}-v@{ub}
@{b}--version@{ub}
@{b}--help@{ub}
     See @{"Standard Options" Link "Standard Options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking uuxqt" "uucp.info/Invoking uuxqt"
@Next "Invoking uuchk"
@Prev "Invoking uucico"
@Toc "Invoking the UUCP Programs"

Invoking uuxqt
==============

     uuxqt [-c command] [-s system] [--command command] [--system system]

   The @{b}uuxqt@{ub} daemon executes commands requested by @{b}uux@{ub} from either the
local system or from remote systems.  It is started automatically by
the @{b}uucico@{ub} daemon (unless @{b}uucico@{ub} is given the @{b}-q@{ub} or @{b}--nouuxqt@{ub} options).

   There is normally no need to run @{b}uuxqt@{ub}, since it will be invoked by
@{b}uucico@{ub}.  However, @{b}uuxqt@{ub} can be invoked directly to provide
greater control over the processing of the work queue.

   Multiple invocations of @{b}uuxqt@{ub} may be run at once, as controlled by
the @{b}max-uuxqts@{ub} configuration command; see @{"Miscellaneous (config)" Link "Miscellaneous (config)"}.

   The following options may be given to @{b}uuxqt@{ub}.

@{b}-c command@{ub}
@{b}--command command@{ub}
     Only execute requests for the specified command.  For example, @{b}uuxqt --command
     rmail@{ub}.

@{b}-s system@{ub}
@{b}--system system@{ub}
     Only execute requests originating from the specified system.

@{b}-x type@{ub}
@{b}--debug type@{ub}
@{b}-I file@{ub}
@{b}--config@{ub}
@{b}-v@{ub}
@{b}--version@{ub}
@{b}--help@{ub}
     See @{"Standard Options" Link "Standard Options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking uuchk" "uucp.info/Invoking uuchk"
@Next "Invoking uuconv"
@Prev "Invoking uuxqt"
@Toc "Invoking the UUCP Programs"

Invoking uuchk
==============

     uuchk [-s system] [--system system]

   The @{b}uuchk@{ub} program displays information read from the UUCP
configuration files.  It should be used to ensure that UUCP has been
configured correctly.

   The @{b}-s@{ub} or @{b}--system@{ub} options may be used to display the configuration
for just the specified system, rather than for all systems.  The @{b}uuchk@{ub}
program also supports the standard UUCP program options; see
@{"Standard Options" Link "Standard Options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking uuconv" "uucp.info/Invoking uuconv"
@Next "Invoking uusched"
@Prev "Invoking uuchk"
@Toc "Invoking the UUCP Programs"

Invoking uuconv
===============

     uuconv -i type -o type [-p program] [--program program]
uuconv --input type --output type [-p program] [--program program]

   The @{b}uuconv@{ub} program converts UUCP configuration files from one format
to another.  The type of configuration file to read is specified using
the @{b}-i@{ub} or @{b}--input@{ub} options.  The type of configuration file to write is
specified using the @{b}-o@{ub} or @{b}--output@{ub} options.

   The supported configuration file types are @{b}taylor@{ub}, @{b}v2@{ub}, and @{b}hdb@{ub}.  For
a description of the @{b}taylor@{ub} configuration files, see
@{"Configuration Files" Link "Configuration Files"}.  The other types of configuration files are used
by traditional UUCP packages, and are not described in this manual.

   An input configuration of type @{b}v2@{ub} or @{b}hdb@{ub} is read from a compiled in
directory (specified by @{b}oldconfigdir@{ub} in @{b}Makefile@{ub}).  An input
configuration of type @{b}taylor@{ub} is read from a compiled in directory by
default, but may be overridden with the standard @{b}-I@{ub} or @{b}--config@{ub} options
(see @{"Standard Options" Link "Standard Options"}).

   The output configuration is written to files in the directory in
which @{b}uuconv@{ub} is run.

   Some information in the input files may not be representable in the
desired output format, in which case @{b}uuconv@{ub} will silently discard it.
The output of @{b}uuconv@{ub} should be carefully checked before it is used.
The @{b}uuchk@{ub} program may be used for this purpose; see @{"Invoking uuchk" Link "Invoking uuchk"}.

   The @{b}-p@{ub} or @{b}--program@{ub} option may be used to convert specific @{b}cu@{ub}
configuration information, rather than the default of only converting
the @{b}uucp@{ub} configuration information; see @{"config File" Link "config File"}.

   The @{b}uuchk@{ub} program also supports the standard UUCP program options;
see @{"Standard Options" Link "Standard Options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Invoking uusched" "uucp.info/Invoking uusched"
@Prev "Invoking uuconv"
@Toc "Invoking the UUCP Programs"

Invoking uusched
================

   The @{b}uusched@{ub} program is actually just a shell script which invokes
the @{b}uucico@{ub} daemon.  It is provided for backward compatibility.  It
causes @{b}uucico@{ub} to call all systems for which there is work.  Any option
which may be given to @{b}uucico@{ub} may also be given to @{b}uusched@{ub}.  See
@{"Invoking uucico" Link "Invoking uucico"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Installing Taylor UUCP" "uucp.info/Installing Taylor UUCP"
@Next "Using Taylor UUCP"
@Prev "Invoking the UUCP Programs"
@Toc "Main"

Installing Taylor UUCP
**********************

   These are the installation instructions for the Taylor UUCP package.


 @{" Compilation               " Link "Compilation"}  Compiling Taylor UUCP
 @{" Testing the Compilation   " Link "Testing the Compilation"}  Testing the Compilation
 @{" Installing the Binaries   " Link "Installing the Binaries"}  Installing the Binaries
 @{" Configuration             " Link "Configuration"}  Configuring Taylor UUCP
 @{" Testing the Installation  " Link "Testing the Installation"}  Testing the Installation


@EndNode

@Node "Compilation" "uucp.info/Compilation"
@Next "Testing the Compilation"
@Prev "Installing Taylor UUCP"
@Toc "Installing Taylor UUCP"

Compiling Taylor UUCP
=====================

   If you have a source code distribution, you must first compile it for
your system.  Free versions of Unix, such as Linux, NetBSD, or FreeBSD,
often come with pre-compiled binary distributions of UUCP.  If you are
using a binary distribution, you may skip to the configuration section
(see @{"Configuration" Link "Configuration"}).

   Follow these steps to compile the source code.

  1. Take a look at the top of @{b}Makefile.in@{ub} and set the appropriate
     values for your system.  These control where the programs are
     installed and which user on the system owns them (normally they
     will be owned by a special user @{b}uucp@{ub} rather than a real person;
     they should probably not be owned by @{b}root@{ub}).

  2. Run the shell script @{b}configure@{ub}.  This script was generated using
     the @{b}autoconf@{ub} program written by David MacKenzie of the Free
     Software Foundation.  It takes a while to run.  It will generate
     the file @{b}config.h@{ub} based on @{b}config.h.in@{ub}, and, for each source code
     directory, will generate @{b}Makefile@{ub} based on @{b}Makefile.in@{ub}.

     You can pass certain arguments to @{b}configure@{ub} in the environment.
     Because @{b}configure@{ub} will compile little test programs to see what is
     available on your system, you must tell it how to run your
     compiler.  It recognizes the following environment variables:

    @{b}CC@{ub}
          The C compiler.  If this is not set, then if @{b}configure@{ub} can
          find @{b}gcc@{ub} it will use it, otherwise it will use @{b}cc@{ub}.

    @{b}CFLAGS@{ub}
          Flags to pass to the C compiler when compiling the actual
          code.  If this is not set, @{b}configure@{ub} will use @{b}-g@{ub}.

    @{b}LDFLAGS@{ub}
          Flags to pass to the C compiler when only linking, not
          compiling.  If this is not set, @{b}configure@{ub} will use the empty
          string.

    @{b}LIBS@{ub}
          Libraries to pass to the C compiler.  If this is not set,
          @{b}configure@{ub} will use the empty string.

    @{b}INSTALL@{ub}
          The program to run to install UUCP in the binary directory.
          If this is not set, then if @{b}configure@{ub} finds the BSD @{b}install@{ub}
          program, it will set this to @{b}install -c@{ub}; otherwise, it will
          use @{b}cp@{ub}.

     Suppose, for example, you want to set the environment variable @{b}CC@{ub}
     to @{b}rcc@{ub}.  If you are using @{b}sh@{ub}, @{b}bash@{ub}, or @{b}ksh@{ub}, invoke @{b}configure@{ub} as @{b}CC=rcc
     configure@{ub}.  If you are using @{b}csh@{ub}, do @{b}setenv CC rcc; sh
     configure@{ub}.

     On some systems you will want to use @{b}LIBS=-lmalloc@{ub}.  On Xenix
     derived versions of Unix do not use @{b}LIBS=-lx@{ub} because this will
     bring in the wrong versions of certain routines; if you want to use
     @{b}-lx@{ub} you must specify @{b}LIBS=-lc -lx@{ub}.

     If @{b}configure@{ub} fails for some reason, or if you have a very weird
     system, you may have to configure the package by hand.  To do
     this, copy the file @{b}config.h.in@{ub} to @{b}config.h@{ub} and edit it for your
     system.  Then for each source directory (the top directory, and the
     subdirectories @{b}lib@{ub}, @{b}unix@{ub}, and @{b}uuconf@{ub}) copy @{b}Makefile.in@{ub} to
     @{b}Makefile@{ub}, find the words within @{b} @@{ub} characters, and set
     them correctly for your system.

  3. Igor V. Semenyuk provided this (lightly edited) note about ISC
     Unix 3.0.  The @{b}configure@{ub} script will default to passing @{b}-posix@{ub} to
     @{b}gcc@{ub}.  However, using @{b}-posix@{ub} changes the environment to
     POSIX, and on ISC 3.0, at least, the default for @{b}POSIX_NO_TRUNC@{ub} is
     1.  This can lead to a problem when @{b}uuxqt@{ub} executes @{b}rmail@{ub}.  @{b}IDA
     sendmail@{ub} has dbm configuration files named
     @{b}mailertable.{dir,pag}@{ub}.  Notice these names are 15
     characters long.  When @{b}uuxqt@{ub} compiled with the @{b}-posix@{ub} executes
     @{b}rmail@{ub}, which in turn executes @{b}sendmail@{ub}, the later is run
     under the POSIX environment too.  This leads to @{b}sendmail@{ub} bombing
     out with @{b}'error opening 'M' database: name too long'
     (mailertable.dir)@{ub}.  It's rather obscure behaviour, and it
     took me a day to find out the cause.  I don't use the @{b}-posix@{ub}
     switch; instead, I run @{b}gcc@{ub} with @{b}-D_POSIX_SOURCE@{ub}, and add @{b}-lcposix@{ub}
     to @{b}LIBS@{ub}.

  4. On some versions of BSDI there is a bug in the shell which causes
     the default value for @{b}CFLAGS@{ub} to be set incorrectly.  If @{b}echo
     ${CFLAGS--g}@{ub} echoes @{b}g@{ub} rather than @{b}-g@{ub}, then you must set
     @{b}CFLAGS@{ub} in the environment before running configure.
     There is a patch available from BSDI for this bug.  (Reported by
     David Vrona).

  5. On AIX 3.2.5, and possibly other versions, @{b}cc -E@{ub} does not work,
     reporting @{b}Option NOROCONST is not valid@{ub}.  Test this before running
     configure by doing something like @{b}touch /tmp/foo.c; cc -E
     /tmp/foo.c@{ub}.  This may give a warning about the file being
     empty, but it should not give the @{b}Option NOROCONST@{ub} warning.  The
     workaround is to remove the @{b},noroconst@{ub} entry from the @{b}options@{ub}
     clause in the @{b}cc@{ub} stanza in @{b}/etc/xlc.cfg@{ub}.  (Reported by Chris
     Lewis).

  6. You should verify that @{b}configure@{ub} worked correctly by checking
     @{b}config.h@{ub} and the instances of @{b}Makefile@{ub}.

  7. Edit @{b}policy.h@{ub} for your local system.  The comments explain the
     various choices.  The default values are intended to be
     reasonable, so you may not have to make any changes.

     You must decide what type of configuration files to use; for more
     information on the choices, see @{"Configuration" Link "Configuration"}.

     You must also decide what sort of spool directory you want to use.
     If this is a new installation, I recommend @{b}SPOOLDIR_TAYLOR@{ub};
     otherwise, select the spool directory corresponding to your
     existing UUCP package.

  8. Type @{b}make@{ub} to compile everything.

     The @{b}tstuu.c@{ub} file is not particularly portable; if you can't figure
     out how to compile it you can safely ignore it, as it is only used
     for testing.  To use STREAMS pseudo-terminals, tstuu.c must be
     compiled with @{b}-DHAVE_STREAMS_PTYS@{ub}; this is not determined by the
     configure script.

     If you have any other problems there is probably a bug in the
     @{b}configure@{ub} script.

  9. Please report any problems you have.  That is the only way they
     will get fixed for other people.  Supply a patch if you can (see
     @{"Patches" Link "Patches"}), or just ask for help.



@EndNode

@Node "Testing the Compilation" "uucp.info/Testing the Compilation"
@Next "Installing the Binaries"
@Prev "Compilation"
@Toc "Installing Taylor UUCP"

Testing the Compilation
=======================

   If your system supports pseudo-terminals, and you compiled the code
to support the new style of configuration files (@{b}HAVE_TAYLOR_CONFIG@{ub} was
set to 1 in @{b}policy.h@{ub}), you should be able to use the @{b}tstuu@{ub} program to
test the @{b}uucico@{ub} daemon.  If your system supports STREAMS based
pseudo-terminals, you must compile tstuu.c with @{b}-DHAVE_STREAMS_PTYS@{ub}.
(The STREAMS based code was contributed by Marc Boucher).

   To run @{b}tstuu@{ub}, just type @{b}tstuu@{ub} with no arguments.  You must run it in
the compilation directory, since it runs @{b}./uucp@{ub}, @{b}./uux@{ub} and @{b}./uucico@{ub}.
The @{b}tstuu@{ub} program will run a lengthy series of tests (it takes over ten
minutes on a slow VAX).  You will need a fair amount of space available
in @{b}/usr/tmp@{ub}.  You will probably want to put it in the background.  Do
not use @{b}^Z@{ub}, because the program traps on @{b}SIGCHLD@{ub} and winds up dying.
The @{b}tstuu@{ub} program will create a directory @{b}/usr/tmp/tstuu@{ub} and fill it
with configuration files, and create spool directories
@{b}/usr/tmp/tstuu/spool1@{ub} and @{b}/usr/tmp/tstuu/spool2@{ub}.

   If your system does not support the @{b}FIONREAD@{ub} call, the @{b}tstuu@{ub} program
will run very slowly.  This may or may not get fixed in a later version.

   The @{b}tstuu@{ub} program will finish with an execute file named @{b}X.@{I}SOMETHING@{ui}@{ub}
and a data file named @{b}D.@{I}SOMETHING@{ui}@{ub} in the directory
@{b}/usr/tmp/tstuu/spool1@{ub} (or, more likely, in subdirectories,
depending on the choice of @{b}SPOOLDIR@{ub} in @{b}policy.h@{ub}).  Two log files will
be created in the directory @{b}/usr/tmp/tstuu@{ub}.  They will be named @{b}Log1@{ub}
and @{b}Log2@{ub}, or, if you have selected @{b}HAVE_HDB_LOGGING@{ub} in @{b}policy.h@{ub},
@{b}Log1/uucico/test2@{ub} and @{b}Log2/uucico/test1@{ub}.  There should be no
errors in the log files.

   You can test @{b}uuxqt@{ub} with @{b}./uuxqt -I /usr/tmp/tstuu/Config1@{ub}.  This
should leave a command file @{b}C.@{I}SOMETHING@{ui}@{ub} and a data file @{b}D.@{I}SOMETHING@{ui}@{ub} in
@{b}/usr/tmp/tstuu/spool1@{ub} or in subdirectories.  Again, there
should be no errors in the log file.

   Assuming you compiled the code with debugging enabled, the @{b}-x@{ub} switch
can be used to set debugging modes; see the @{b}debug@{ub} command for details
(see @{"Debugging Levels" Link "Debugging Levels"}).  Use @{b}-x all@{ub} to turn on all debugging and
generate far more output than you will ever want to see.  The @{b}uucico@{ub}
daemons will put debugging output in the files @{b}Debug1@{ub} and @{b}Debug2@{ub} in the
directory @{b}/usr/tmp/tstuu@{ub}.  After that, you're pretty much on your own.

   On some systems you can also use @{b}tstuu@{ub} to test @{b}uucico@{ub} against the
system @{b}uucico@{ub}, by using the @{b}-u@{ub} switch.  For this to work, change the
definitions of @{b}ZUUCICO_CMD@{ub} and @{b}UUCICO_EXECL@{ub} at the top of @{b}tstuu.c@{ub} to
something appropriate for your system.  The definitions in @{b}tstuu.c@{ub} are
what I used for Ultrix 4.0, on which @{b}/usr/lib/uucp/uucico@{ub} is
particularly obstinate about being run as a child; I was only able to
run it by creating a login name with no password whose shell was
@{b}/usr/lib/uucp/uucico@{ub}.  Calling login in this way will leave
fake entries in @{b}wtmp@{ub} and @{b}utmp@{ub}; if you compile @{b}tstout.c@{ub} (in the @{b}contrib@{ub}
directory) as a setuid @{b}root@{ub} program, @{b}tstuu@{ub} will run it to clear those
entries out.  On most systems, such hackery should not be necessary,
although on SCO I had to su to @{b}root@{ub} (@{b}uucp@{ub} might also have worked)
before I could run @{b}/usr/lib/uucp/uucico@{ub}.

   You can test @{b}uucp@{ub} and @{b}uux@{ub} (give them the @{b}-r@{ub} switch to keep them from
starting @{b}uucico@{ub}) to make sure they create the right sorts of files.
Unfortunately, if you don't know what the right sorts of files are, I'm
not going to tell you here.

   If you can not run @{b}tstuu@{ub}, or if it fails inexplicably, don't worry
about it too much.  On some systems @{b}tstuu@{ub} will fail because of problems
using pseudo terminals, which will not matter in normal use.  The real
test of the package is talking to another system.


@EndNode

@Node "Installing the Binaries" "uucp.info/Installing the Binaries"
@Next "Configuration"
@Prev "Testing the Compilation"
@Toc "Installing Taylor UUCP"

Installing the Binaries
=======================

   You can install the executable files by becoming @{b}root@{ub} and typing @{b}make
install@{ub}.  Or you can look at what @{b}make install@{ub} does and do it by
hand.  It tries to preserve your old programs, if any, but it only does
this the first time Taylor UUCP is installed (so that if you install
several versions of Taylor UUCP, you can still go back to your original
UUCP programs).  You can retrieve the original programs by typing @{b}make
uninstall@{ub}.

   Note that by default the programs are compiled with debugging
information, and they are not stripped when they are installed.  You may
want to strip the installed programs to save disk space.  For more
information, see your system documentation for the @{b}strip@{ub} program.

   Of course, simply installing the executable files is not enough.  You
must also arrange for them to be used correctly.


@EndNode

@Node "Configuration" "uucp.info/Configuration"
@Next "Testing the Installation"
@Prev "Installing the Binaries"
@Toc "Installing Taylor UUCP"

Configuring Taylor UUCP
=======================

   You will have to decide what types of configuration files you want to
use.  This package supports a new sort of configuration file; see
@{"Configuration Files" Link "Configuration Files"}.  It also supports V2 configuration files (@{b}L.sys@{ub},
@{b}L-devices@{ub}, etc.) and HDB configuration files (@{b}Systems@{ub},
@{b}Devices@{ub}, etc.).  No documentation is provided for V2 or HDB
configuration files.  All types of configuration files can be used at
once, if you are so inclined.  Currently using just V2 configuration
files is not really possible, because there is no way to specify a
dialer (there are no built in dialers, and the program does not know
how to read @{b}acucap@{ub} or @{b}modemcap@{ub}); however, V2 configuration files can be
used with a new style dial file (see @{"dial File" Link "dial File"}), or with a HDB @{b}Dialers@{ub}
file.

   Use of HDB configuration files has two known bugs.  A blank line in
the middle of an entry in the @{b}Permissions@{ub} file will not be ignored as
it should be.  Dialer programs, as found in some versions of HDB, are
not recognized directly.  If you must use a dialer program, rather than
an entry in @{b}Devices@{ub}, you must use the @{b}chat-program@{ub} command in a new
style dial file; see @{"dial File" Link "dial File"}.  You will have to invoke the dialer
program via a shell script or another program, since an exit code of 0
is required to recognize success; the @{b}dialHDB@{ub} program in the @{b}contrib@{ub}
directory may be used for this purpose.

   The @{b}uuconv@{ub} (see @{"Invoking uuconv" Link "Invoking uuconv"}) program can be used to convert from
V2 or HDB configuration files to the new style (it can also do the
reverse translation, if you are so inclined).  It will not do all of
the work, and the results should be carefully checked, but it can be
quite useful.

   If you are installing a new system, you will, of course, have to
write the configuration files; see @{"Configuration Files" Link "Configuration Files"} for details on
how to do this.

   After writing the configuration files, use the @{b}uuchk@{ub} program to
verify that they are what you expect; see @{"Invoking uuchk" Link "Invoking uuchk"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Testing the Installation" "uucp.info/Testing the Installation"
@Prev "Configuration"
@Toc "Installing Taylor UUCP"

Testing the Installation
========================

   After you have written the configuration files, and verified them
with the @{b}uuchk@{ub} program (see @{"Invoking uuchk" Link "Invoking uuchk"}), you must check that UUCP
can correctly contact another system.

   Tell @{b}uucico@{ub} to dial out to the system by using the @{b}-s@{ub} system switch
(e.g., @{b}uucico -s uunet@{ub}).  The log file should tell you what happens.
The exact location of the log file depends upon the settings in
@{b}policy.h@{ub} when you compiled the program, and on the use of the
@{b}logfile@{ub} command in the @{b}config@{ub} file.  Typical locations are
@{b}/usr/spool/uucp/Log@{ub} or a subdirectory under
@{b}/usr/spool/uucp/.Log@{ub}.

   If you compiled the code with debugging enabled, you can use
debugging mode to get a great deal of information about what sort of
data is flowing back and forth; the various possibilities are described
with the @{b}debug@{ub} command (see @{"Debugging Levels" Link "Debugging Levels"}).  When initially setting
up a connection @{b}-x chat@{ub} is probably the most useful (e.g., @{b}uucico -s uunet -x
chat@{ub}); you may also want to use @{b}-x handshake,incoming,outgoing@{ub}.
You can use @{b}-x@{ub} multiple times on one command line, or you can give it
comma separated arguments as in the last example.  Use @{b}-x all@{ub} to turn
on all possible debugging information.

   The debugging information is written to a file, normally
@{b}/usr/spool/uucp/Debug@{ub}, although the default can be changed in
@{b}policy.h@{ub}, and the @{b}config@{ub} file can override the default with
the @{b}debugfile@{ub} command.  The debugging file may contain passwords and
some file contents as they are transmitted over the line, so the
debugging file is only readable by the @{b}uucp@{ub} user.

   You can use the @{b}-f@{ub} switch to force @{b}uucico@{ub} to call out even if the
last call failed recently; using @{b}-S@{ub} when naming a system has the same
effect.  Otherwise the status file (in the @{b}.Status@{ub} subdirectory of the
main spool directory, normally @{b}/usr/spool/uucp@{ub}) (see @{"Status Directory" Link "Status Directory"})
will prevent too many attempts from occurring in rapid succession.

   On older System V based systems which do not have the @{b}setreuid@{ub}
system call, problems may arise if ordinary users can start an execution
of @{b}uuxqt@{ub}, perhaps indirectly via @{b}uucp@{ub} or @{b}uux@{ub}.  UUCP jobs may wind up
executing with a real user ID of the user who invoked @{b}uuxqt@{ub}, which can
cause problems if the UUCP job checks the real user ID for security
purposes.  On such systems, it is safest to put @{b}run-uuxqt never@{ub} (see
@{"Miscellaneous (config)" Link "Miscellaneous (config)"}) in the @{b}config@{ub} file, so that @{b}uucico@{ub} never starts
@{b}uuxqt@{ub}, and invoke @{b}uuxqt@{ub} directly from a @{b}crontab@{ub} file.

   Please let me know about any problems you have and how you got around
them.  If you do report a problem, please include the version number of
the package you are using, the operating system you are running it on,
and a sample of the debugging file showing the problem (debugging
information is usually what is needed, not just the log file).  General
questions such as "why doesn't @{b}uucico@{ub} dial out" are impossible to
answer without much more information.


@EndNode

@Node "Using Taylor UUCP" "uucp.info/Using Taylor UUCP"
@Next "Configuration Files"
@Prev "Installing Taylor UUCP"
@Toc "Main"

Using Taylor UUCP
*****************


 @{" Calling Other Systems     " Link "Calling Other Systems"}  Calling Other Systems
 @{" Accepting Calls           " Link "Accepting Calls"}  Accepting Calls
 @{" Mail and News             " Link "Mail and News"}  Using UUCP for Mail and News
 @{" The Spool Directory Layout " Link "The Spool Directory Layout"}  The Spool Directory Layout
 @{" Spool Directory Cleaning  " Link "Spool Directory Cleaning"}  Cleaning the UUCP Spool Directory


@EndNode

@Node "Calling Other Systems" "uucp.info/Calling Other Systems"
@Next "Accepting Calls"
@Prev "Using Taylor UUCP"
@Toc "Using Taylor UUCP"

Calling Other Systems
=====================

   By default @{b}uucp@{ub} and @{b}uux@{ub} will automatically start up @{b}uucico@{ub} to call
another system whenever work is queued up.  However, the call may fail,
or you may have put in time restrictions which prevent the call at that
time (perhaps because telephone rates are high) (see @{"When to Call" Link "When to Call"}).
Also, a remote system may have work queued up for your system, but may
not be calling you for some reason (perhaps you have agreed that your
system should always place the call).  To make sure that work gets
transferred between the systems withing a reasonable time period, you
should arrange to periodically invoke @{b}uucico@{ub}.

   These periodic invocations are normally triggered by entries in the
@{b}crontab@{ub} file.  The exact format of @{b}crontab@{ub} files, and how new
entries are added, varies from system to system; check your local
documentation (try @{b}man cron@{ub}).

   To attempt to call all systems with outstanding work, use the command
@{b}uucico -r1@{ub}.  To attempt to call a particular system, use the
command @{b}uucico -s @{I}SYSTEM@{ui}@{ub}.  To attempt to call a particular system, but
only if there is work for it, use the command @{b}uucico -C -s @{I}SYSTEM@{ui}@{ub}.
(see @{"Invoking uucico" Link "Invoking uucico"}).

   A common case is to want to try to call a system at a certain time,
with periodic retries if the call fails.  A simple way to do this is to
create an empty UUCP command file, known as a @{i}poll file@{ui}.  If a poll
file exists for a system, then @{b}uucico -r1@{ub} will place a call to it.  If
the call succeeds, the poll file will be deleted.

   A poll file can be easily created using the @{b}uux@{ub} command, by
requesting the execution of an empty command.  To create a poll file for
@{I}SYSTEM@{ui}, just do something like this:
     uux -r @{I}SYSTEM@{ui}!
   The @{b}-r@{ub} tells @{b}uux@{ub} to not start up @{b}uucico@{ub} immediately.  Of course, if
you do want @{b}uucico@{ub} to start up right away, omit the @{b}-r@{ub}; if the call
fails, the poll file will be left around to cause a later call.

   For example, I use the following crontab entries locally:

     45 * * * * /bin/echo /usr/lib/uucp/uucico -r1 | /bin/su uucpa
40 4,10,15 * * * /usr/bin/uux -r uunet!

   Every hour, at 45 minutes past, this will check if there is any work
to be done, and, if there is, will call the appropriate system.  Also,
at 4:40am, 10:40am, and 3:40pm, this will create a poll file file for
@{b}uunet@{ub}, forcing the next run of @{b}uucico@{ub} to call @{b}uunet@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Accepting Calls" "uucp.info/Accepting Calls"
@Next "Mail and News"
@Prev "Calling Other Systems"
@Toc "Using Taylor UUCP"

Accepting Calls
===============

   To accept calls from another system, you must arrange matters such
that when that system calls in, it automatically invokes @{b}uucico@{ub} on your
system.

   The most common arrangement is to create a special user name and
password for incoming UUCP calls.  This user name typically uses the
same user ID as the regular @{b}uucp@{ub} user (Unix permits several user names
to share the same user ID).  The shell for this user name should be set
to @{b}uucico@{ub}.

   Here is a sample @{b}/etc/passwd@{ub} line to accept calls from a remote
system named airs:
     Uairs:@{I}PASSWORD@{ui}:4:8:airs UUCP:/usr/spool/uucp:/usr/lib/uucp/uucico
   The details may vary on your system.  You must use reasonable user
and group ID's.  You must use the correct file name for @{b}uucico@{ub}.  The
@{I}PASSWORD@{ui} must appear in the UUCP configuration files on the
remote system, but will otherwise never be seen or typed by a human.

   Note that @{b}uucico@{ub} appears as the login shell, and that it will be run
with no arguments.  This means that it will start in slave mode and
accept an incoming connection.  See @{"Invoking uucico" Link "Invoking uucico"}.

   On some systems, creating an empty file named @{b}.hushlogin@{ub} in the home
directory will skip the printing of various bits of information when
the remote @{b}uucico@{ub} logs in, speeding up the UUCP connection process.

   For the greatest security, each system which calls in should use a
different user name, each with a different password, and the
@{b}called-login@{ub} command should be used in the @{b}sys@{ub} file to ensure
that the correct login name is used.  See @{"Accepting a Call" Link "Accepting a Call"}, and see
@{"Security" Link "Security"}.

   If you never need to dial out from your system, but only accept
incoming calls, you can arrange for @{b}uucico@{ub} to handle logins itself,
completely controlling the port, by using the @{b}--endless@{ub} option.  See
@{"Invoking uucico" Link "Invoking uucico"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Mail and News" "uucp.info/Mail and News"
@Next "The Spool Directory Layout"
@Prev "Accepting Calls"
@Toc "Using Taylor UUCP"

Using UUCP for Mail and News.
=============================

   Taylor UUCP does not include a mail package.  All Unix systems come
with some sort of mail delivery agent, typically @{b}sendmail@{ub} or @{b}MMDF@{ub}.
Source code is available for some alternative mail delivery agents,
such as @{b}IDA sendmail@{ub} and @{b}smail@{ub}.

   Taylor UUCP also does not include a news package.  The two major Unix
news packages are @{b}C-news@{ub} and @{b}INN@{ub}.  Both are available in source code
form.

   Configuring and using mail delivery agents is a notoriously complex
topic, and I will not be discussing it here.  Configuring news systems
is usually simpler, but I will not be discussing that either.  I will
merely describe the interactions between the mail and news systems and
UUCP.

   A mail or news system interacts with UUCP in two ways: sending and
receiving.


 @{" Sending mail or news      " Link "Sending mail or news"}  Sending mail or news via UUCP
 @{" Receiving mail or news    " Link "Receiving mail or news"}  Receiving mail or news via UUCP


@EndNode

@Node "Sending mail or news" "uucp.info/Sending mail or news"
@Next "Receiving mail or news"
@Prev "Mail and News"
@Toc "Mail and News"

Sending mail or news via UUCP
-----------------------------

   When mail is to be sent from your machine to another machine via
UUCP, the mail delivery agent will invoke @{b}uux@{ub}.  It will generally run a
command such as @{b}uux - @{I}SYSTEM@{ui}!rmail @{I}ADDRESS@{ui}@{ub}, where @{I}SYSTEM@{ui} is the remote
system to which the mail is being sent.  It may pass other options to
@{b}uux@{ub}, such as @{b}-r@{ub} or @{b}-g@{ub} (see @{"Invoking uux" Link "Invoking uux"}).

   The news system also invokes @{b}uux@{ub} in order to transfer articles to
another system.  The only difference is that news will use @{b}uux@{ub} to
invoke @{b}rnews@{ub} on the remote system, rather than @{b}rmail@{ub}.

   You should arrange for your mail and news systems to invoke the
Taylor UUCP version of @{b}uux@{ub}.  If you only have Taylor UUCP, or if you
simply replace any existing version of @{b}uux@{ub} with the Taylor UUCP
version, this will probably happen automatically.  However, if you have
two UUCP packages installed on your system, you will probably have to
modify the mail and news configuration files in some way.

   Actually, if both the system UUCP and Taylor UUCP are using the same
spool directory format, the system @{b}uux@{ub} will probably work fine with the
Taylor @{b}uucico@{ub} (the reverse is not the case: the Taylor @{b}uux@{ub} requires the
Taylor @{b}uucico@{ub}).  However, data transfer will be somewhat more efficient
if the Taylor @{b}uux@{ub} is used.


@EndNode

@Node "Receiving mail or news" "uucp.info/Receiving mail or news"
@Prev "Sending mail or news"
@Toc "Mail and News"

Receiving mail or news via UUCP
-------------------------------

   To receive mail, all that is necessary is for UUCP to invoke @{b}rmail@{ub}.
Any mail delivery agent will provide an appropriate version of @{b}rmail@{ub};
you must simply make sure that it is in the command path used by UUCP
(it almost certainly already is).  The default command path is set in
@{b}policy.h@{ub}, and it may be overridden for a particular system by
the @{b}command-path@{ub} command (see @{"Miscellaneous (sys)" Link "Miscellaneous (sys)"}).

   Similarly, for news UUCP must be able to invoke @{b}rnews@{ub}.  Any news
system will provide a version of @{b}rnews@{ub}, and you must ensure that is in
a directory on the path that UUCP will search.


@EndNode

@Node "The Spool Directory Layout" "uucp.info/The Spool Directory Layout"
@Next "Spool Directory Cleaning"
@Prev "Mail and News"
@Toc "Using Taylor UUCP"

The Spool Directory Layout
==========================

   In general, the layout of the spool directory may be safely ignored.
However, it is documented here for the curious.  This description only
covers the @{b}SPOOLDIR_TAYLOR@{ub} layout.  The ways in which the other spool
directory layouts differ are described in the source file @{b}unix/spool.c@{ub}.

   Directories and files are only created when they are needed, so a
typical system will not have all of the entries described here.


 @{" System Spool Directories  " Link "System Spool Directories"}  System Spool Directories
 @{" Status Directory          " Link "Status Directory"}  Status Spool Directory
 @{" Execution Subdirectories  " Link "Execution Subdirectories"}  Execution Spool Subdirectories
 @{" Other Spool Subdirectories " Link "Other Spool Subdirectories"}  Other Spool Subdirectories
 @{" Spool Lock Files          " Link "Spool Lock Files"}  Spool Directory Lock Files


@EndNode

@Node "System Spool Directories" "uucp.info/System Spool Directories"
@Next "Status Directory"
@Prev "The Spool Directory Layout"
@Toc "The Spool Directory Layout"

System Spool Directories
------------------------

@{b}@{I}SYSTEM@{ui}@{ub}
     There is a subdirectory of the main spool directory for each remote
     system.

@{b}@{I}SYSTEM@{ui}/C.@{ub}
     This directory stores files describing file transfer commands to
     be sent to the @{I}SYSTEM@{ui}.  Each file name starts with @{b}C.@{I}G@{ui}@{ub}, where @{I}G@{ui} is
     the job grade.  Each file contains one or more commands.  For
     details of the commands, see @{"UUCP Protocol Commands" Link "UUCP Protocol Commands"}.

@{b}@{I}SYSTEM@{ui}/D.@{ub}
     This directory stores data files.  Files with names like @{b}D.@{I}G@{ui} @{I}SSSS@{ui}@{ub},
     where @{I}G@{ui} is the grade and @{I}SSSS@{ui} is a sequence number, are waiting to
     be transferred to the @{I}SYSTEM@{ui}, as directed by the files in the
     @{b}@{I}SYSTEM@{ui}/C.@{ub} directory.  Files with other names,
     typically @{b}D.@{I}SYSTEM@{ui} @{I}G@{ui} @{I}SSSS@{ui}@{ub}, have been received from @{I}SYSTEM@{ui} and are
     waiting to be processed by an execution file in the @{b}@{I}SYSTEM@{ui}/X.@{ub}
     directory.

@{b}@{I}SYSTEM@{ui}/D.X@{ub}
     This directory stores data files which will become execution files
     on the remote system.  In current practice, this directory rarely
     exists, because most simple executions, including typical uses of @{b}rmail@{ub}
     and @{b}rnews@{ub}, send an @{b}E@{ub} command rather than an execution file (see
     @{"The E Command" Link "The E Command"}).

@{b}@{I}SYSTEM@{ui}/X.@{ub}
     This directory stores execution files which have been received from
     @{I}SYSTEM@{ui}.  This directory normally exists, even though the
     corresponding @{b}D.X@{ub} directory does not, because @{b}uucico@{ub} will create
     an execution file on the fly when it receives an @{b}E@{ub} command.

@{b}@{I}SYSTEM@{ui}/SEQF@{ub}
     This file holds the sequence number of the last job sent to
     @{I}SYSTEM@{ui}.  The sequence number is used to ensure that file
     names are unique in the remote system spool directory.  The file
     is four bytes long.  Sequence numbers are composed of digits and
     the upper case letters.


@EndNode

@Node "Status Directory" "uucp.info/Status Directory"
@Next "Execution Subdirectories"
@Prev "System Spool Directories"
@Toc "The Spool Directory Layout"

Status Directory
----------------

@{b}.Status@{ub}
     This directory holds status files for each remote system.  The
     name of the status file is the name of the system which it
     describes.  Each status file describes the last conversation with
     the system.  Running @{b}uustat --status@{ub} basically just formats and
     prints the contents of the status files (see @{"uustat Examples" Link "uustat Examples"}).

     Each status file has a single text line with six fields.

    code
          A code indicating the status of the last conversation.  The
          following values are defined, though not all are actually
          used.
         @{b}0@{ub}
               Conversation completed normally.

         @{b}1@{ub}
               @{b}uucico@{ub} was unable to open the port.

         @{b}2@{ub}
               The last call to the system failed while dailing.

         @{b}3@{ub}
               The last call to the system failed while logging in.

         @{b}4@{ub}
               The last call to the system failed during the initial
               UUCP protocol handshake (see @{"The Initial Handshake" Link "The Initial Handshake"}).

         @{b}5@{ub}
               The last call to the system failed after the initial
               handshake.

         @{b}6@{ub}
               @{b}uucico@{ub} is currently talking to the system.

         @{b}7@{ub}
               The last call to the system failed because it was the
               wrong time to call (this is not used if calling the
               system is never permitted).

    retries
          The number of retries since the last successful call.

    time of last call
          The time of the last call, in seconds since the epoch (as
          returned by the @{b}time@{ub} system call).

    wait
          If the last call failed, this is the number of seconds since
          the last call before @{b}uucico@{ub} may attempt another call.  This
          is set based on the retry time; see @{"When to Call" Link "When to Call"}.  The @{b}-f@{ub} or @{b}-S@{ub}
          options to @{b}uucico@{ub} direct it to ignore this wait time; see
          @{"Invoking uucico" Link "Invoking uucico"}.

    description
          A text description of the status, corresponding to the code
          in the first field.  This may contain spaces.

    system name
          The name of the remote system.


@EndNode

@Node "Execution Subdirectories" "uucp.info/Execution Subdirectories"
@Next "Other Spool Subdirectories"
@Prev "Status Directory"
@Toc "The Spool Directory Layout"

Execution Subdirectories
------------------------

@{b}.Xqtdir@{ub}
     When @{b}uuxqt@{ub} executes a job requested by @{b}uux@{ub}, it first changes the
     working directory to the @{b}.Xqtdir@{ub} subdirectory.  This permits the
     job to create any sort of temporary file without worrying about
     overwriting other files in the spool directory.  Any files left in
     the @{b}.Xqtdir@{ub} subdirectory are removed after each execution is
     complete.

@{b}.Xqtdir@{I}NNNN@{ui}@{ub}
     When several instances of @{b}uuxqt@{ub} are executing simultaneously, each
     one executes jobs in a separate directory.  The first uses
     @{b}.Xqtdir@{ub}, the second uses @{b}.Xqtdir0001@{ub}, the third uses
     @{b}.Xqtdir0002@{ub}, and so forth.

@{b}.Corrupt@{ub}
     If @{b}uuxqt@{ub} encounters an execution file which it is unable to parse,
     it saves it in the @{b}.Corrupt@{ub} directory, and sends mail about it to
     the UUCP administrator.

@{b}.Failed@{ub}
     If @{b}uuxqt@{ub} executes a job, and the job fails, and there is enough
     disk space to hold the command file and all the data files, then
     @{b}uuxqt@{ub} saves the files in the @{b}.Failed@{ub} directory, and sends
     mail about it to the UUCP administrator.


@EndNode

@Node "Other Spool Subdirectories" "uucp.info/Other Spool Subdirectories"
@Next "Spool Lock Files"
@Prev "Execution Subdirectories"
@Toc "The Spool Directory Layout"

Other Spool Subdirectories
--------------------------

@{b}.Sequence@{ub}
     This directory holds conversation sequence number files.  These
     are used if the @{b}sequence@{ub} command is used for a system (see
     @{"Miscellaneous (sys)" Link "Miscellaneous (sys)"}).  The sequence number for the system @{I}SYSTEM@{ui}
     is stored in the file @{b}.Sequence/@{I}SYSTEM@{ui}@{ub}.  It is simply stored as a
     printable number.

@{b}.Temp@{ub}
     This directory holds data files as they are being received from a
     remote system, before they are moved to their final destination.
     For file send requests which use a valid temporary file name in
     the @{I}TEMP@{ui} field of the @{b}S@{ub} or @{b}E@{ub} command (see @{"The S Command" Link "The S Command"}), @{b}uucico@{ub}
     receives the file into @{b}.Temp/@{I}SYSTEM@{ui}/@{I}TEMP@{ui}@{ub}, where @{I}SYSTEM@{ui} is the name
     of the remote system, and @{I}TEMP@{ui} is the temporary file name.  If a
     conversation fails during a file transfer, these files are used to
     automatically restart the file transfer from the point of failure.

     If the @{b}S@{ub} or @{b}E@{ub} command does not include a temporary file name,
     automatic restart is not possible.  In this case, the files are
     received into a randomly named file in the @{b}.Temp@{ub} directory itself.

@{b}.Preserve@{ub}
     This directory holds data files which could not be transferred to a
     remote system for some reason (for example, the data file might be
     large, and exceed size restrictions imposed by the remote system).
     When a locally requested file transfer fails, @{b}uucico@{ub} will store
     the data file in the @{b}.Preserve@{ub} directory, and send mail to the
     requestor describing the failure and naming the saved file.

@{b}.Received@{ub}
     This directory records which files have been received.  If a
     conversation fails just after @{b}uucico@{ub} acknowledges receipt of a
     file, it is possible for the acknowledgement to be lost.  If this
     happens, the remote system will resend the file.  If the file were
     an execution request, and @{b}uucico@{ub} did not keep track of which files
     it had already received, this could lead to the execution being
     performed twice.

     To avoid this problem, when a conversation fails, @{b}uucico@{ub} records
     each file that has been received, but for which the remote system
     may not have received the acknowledgement.  It records this
     information by creating an empty file with the name
     @{b}.Received/@{I}SYSTEM@{ui}/@{I}TEMP@{ui}@{ub}, where @{I}SYSTEM@{ui} is
     the name of the remote system, and @{I}TEMP@{ui} is the @{I}TEMP@{ui} field of the @{b}S@{ub}
     or @{b}E@{ub} command from the remote system (see @{"The S Command" Link "The S Command"}).  Then, if
     the remote system offers the file again in the next conversation,
     @{b}uucico@{ub} refuses the send request and deletes the record in
     the @{b}.Received@{ub} directory.  This approach only works for file sends
     which use a temporary file name, but this is true of all execution
     requests.


@EndNode

@Node "Spool Lock Files" "uucp.info/Spool Lock Files"
@Prev "Other Spool Subdirectories"
@Toc "The Spool Directory Layout"

Lock Files in the Spool Directory
---------------------------------

   Lock files for devices and systems are stored in the lock directory,
which may or may not be the same as the spool directory.  The lock
directory is set at compilation time by @{b}LOCKDIR@{ub} in @{b}policy.h@{ub}, which may
be overridden by the @{b}lockdir@{ub} command in the @{b}config@{ub} file (see
@{"Miscellaneous (config)" Link "Miscellaneous (config)"}).

   For a description of the names used for device lock files, and the
format of the contents of a lock file, see @{"UUCP Lock Files" Link "UUCP Lock Files"}.

@{b}LCK..@{I}SYS@{ui}@{ub}
     A lock file for a system, where @{I}SYS@{ui} is the system name.  As noted
     above, these lock files are kept in the lock directory, which may
     not be the spool directory.  These lock files are created by @{b}uucico@{ub}
     while talking to a remote system, and are used to prevent multiple
     simultaneous conversations with a system.

     On systems which limit file names to 14 characters, only the first
     eight characters of the system name are used in the lock file
     name.  This requires that the names of each directly connected
     remote system be unique in the first eight characters.

@{b}LCK.XQT.@{I}NN@{ui}@{ub}
     When @{b}uuxqt@{ub} starts up, it uses lock files to determine how many
     other @{b}uuxqt@{ub} daemons are currently running.  It first tries to lock
     @{b}LCK.XQT.0@{ub}, then @{b}LCK.XQT.1@{ub}, and so forth.  This is used to
     implement the @{b}max-uuxqts@{ub} command (see @{"Miscellaneous (config)" Link "Miscellaneous (config)"}).  It
     is also used to parcel out the @{b}.Xqtdir@{ub} subdirectories (see
     @{"Execution Subdirectories" Link "Execution Subdirectories"}).

@{b}LXQ.@{I}CMD@{ui}@{ub}
     When @{b}uuxqt@{ub} is invoked with the @{b}-c@{ub} or @{b}--command@{ub} option (see
     @{"Invoking uuxqt" Link "Invoking uuxqt"}), it creates a lock file named after the command it
     is executing.  For example, @{b}uuxqt -c rmail@{ub} will create the lock
     file @{b}LXQ.rmail@{ub}.  This prevents other @{b}uuxqt@{ub} daemons from executing
     jobs of the specified type.

@{b}@{I}SYSTEM@{ui}/X./L.@{I}XXX@{ui}@{ub}
     While @{b}uuxqt@{ub} is executing a particular job, it creates a lock file
     with the same name as the @{b}X.@{ub} file describing the job, but
     replacing the initial @{b}X@{ub} with @{b}L@{ub}.  This ensures that if multiple
     @{b}uuxqt@{ub} daemons are running, they do not simultaneously
     execute the same job.

@{b}LCK..SEQ@{ub}
     This lock file is used to control access to the sequence files for
     each system (see @{"System Spool Directories" Link "System Spool Directories"}).  It is only used on
     systems which do not support POSIX file locking using the @{b}fcntl@{ub}
     system call.


@EndNode

@Node "Spool Directory Cleaning" "uucp.info/Spool Directory Cleaning"
@Prev "The Spool Directory Layout"
@Toc "Using Taylor UUCP"

Cleaning the Spool Directory
============================

   The spool directory may need to be cleaned up periodically.  Under
some circumstances, files may accumulate in various subdirectories,
such as @{b}.Preserve@{ub} (see @{"Other Spool Subdirectories" Link "Other Spool Subdirectories"}) or @{b}.Corrupt@{ub} (see
@{"Execution Subdirectories" Link "Execution Subdirectories"}).

   Also, if a remote system stops calling in, you may want to arrange
for any queued up mail to be returned to the sender.  This can be done
using the @{b}uustat@{ub} command (see @{"Invoking uustat" Link "Invoking uustat"}).

   The @{b}contrib@{ub} directory includes a simple @{b}uuclean@{ub} script which may be
used as an example of a clean up script.  It can be run daily out of
@{b}crontab@{ub}.

   You should periodically trim the UUCP log files, as they will
otherwise grow without limit.  The names of the log files are set in
@{b}policy.h@{ub}, and may be overridden in the configuration file (see
@{"config File" Link "config File"}).  By default they are are @{b}/usr/spool/uucp/Log@{ub} and
@{b}/usr/spool/uucp/Stats@{ub}.  You may find the @{b}savelog@{ub} program in
the @{b}contrib@{ub} directory to be of use.  There is a manual page for it in
@{b}contrib@{ub} as well.


@EndNode

@Node "Configuration Files" "uucp.info/Configuration Files"
@Next "Protocols"
@Prev "Using Taylor UUCP"
@Toc "Main"

Taylor UUCP Configuration Files
*******************************

   This chapter describes the configuration files accepted by the Taylor
UUCP package if compiled with @{b}HAVE_TAYLOR_CONFIG@{ub} set to 1 in @{b}policy.h@{ub}.

   The configuration files are normally found in the directory
@{I}NEWCONFIGDIR@{ui}, which is defined by the @{b}Makefile@{ub} variable
@{b}newconfigdir@{ub}; by default @{I}NEWCONFIGDIR@{ui} is @{b}/usr/local/conf/uucp@{ub}.
However, the main configuration file, @{b}config@{ub}, is the only one which
must be in that directory, since it may specify a different location
for any or all of the other files.  You may run any of the UUCP
programs with a different main configuration file by using the @{b}-I@{ub} or
@{b}--config@{ub} option; this can be useful when testing a new
configuration.  When you use the @{b}-I@{ub} option the programs will revoke any
setuid privileges.


 @{" Configuration Overview    " Link "Configuration Overview"}  Configuration File Overview
